$3 \times \frac{1}{2} \times 500 \times (1.53 - 1.397)^2 \times 10^{-20} = 3 \times \frac{1}{2} \times 500 \times (0.133)^2 \times 10^{-20} = 3 \times 250 \times 0.017689 \times 10^{-20} = 13.267 \times 10^{-20} \, \text{J}$.

## Step 5: Calculate the energy required to stretch three carbon-carbon double bonds to the benzene bond length.
The energy to stretch one double bond is $\frac{1}{2} \times 950 \, \text{N/m} \times (1.397 - 1.335)^2 \times 10^{-20} \, \text{J}$. Thus, for three double bonds, it is $3 \times \frac{1}{2} \times 950 \times (1.397 - 1.335)^2 \times 10^{-20} \, \text{J}$.

